<dl id="n14030a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14030a">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14030a"> 30(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> quaff ~ <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n14030a"><li>FW 4.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n14030a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n14030a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n14030a">MS BL 47472a-89v</ms> </li><li>JJA 44:012 <a name="a1A0d" href="../../ff/fdra/ada.htm#a1A0d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/a1a0d.htm#n14030a">Draft: I.1&sect;1A.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">So also did this singer hold up to contumacy the materialism and immortality of the Roman hierarchy, who &ldquo;filled their Guelphish coffers&rdquo; with German gold and silver, in order that their &ldquo;priests might <mark>eat capons and quaff wine</mark>,&rdquo; while Germans &ldquo;prayed and fasted for them.&rdquo; The farce of Absolution came equally under the sting of his lash, von der Vogelweide solemnly asserting that God alone had the power to forgive sins, and that a Pope who dared to assume this right, without first having convinced himself of the sinner&apos;s penitence, deserved to be stoned as soon as ever he consigned one man to hell. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 4-5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
